@article{Zhou2025,
abstract = {The black carp, a significant freshwater aquaculture species in China, has experienced a decline in natural populations and germplasm degradation due to human activities and breeding mismanagement. This study involved the selection of 550 individuals from the Hanjiang population for resequencing. Body length and weight were the measured for growth traits. The use of GATK software for variant detection and VCFtools for quality control resulted in 8,654,359 high-quality SNPs. GWAS analyses were conducted for both traits, with a significance threshold of -log10(p) = 7.8. Significant SNPs identified included 12 for body weight and 1 for body length, with the locus Chr05_42,410,277 being significant for both traits and located on chromosome 5. The annotation of candidate genes revealed several potentially relevant genes, including NLRP3, DHRS12, ATP-dependent 6, SLC12A2, and IGKV4–1. These genes are primarily involved in processes such as immune regulation, food uptake, energy metabolism, and signal regulation. Exploring potential genes and regions related to the growth of black carp through resequencing association analysis offers theoretical insights for genetic research and molecular marker-assisted breeding in black carp. It also supports sustainable aquaculture practices, which are crucial for the conservation and utilization of fishery resources.},
