@article{Sun2025,
abstract = {Trachinotus ovatus is one of the most commercial species in marine aquaculture, making it crucial to investigate the molecular basis underlying its growth-related traits, such as total length (TL). This study had two main objectives: first, to evaluate the influence of genotype imputation on the detection power of genome-wide association studies (GWAS); and second, to screen potential candidate genes affecting growth-related traits in T. ovatus. In this study, a high-quality haplotype reference panel was developed using high coverage resequencing data from 199 individuals representing different populations. The genomic variant dataset was obtained by imputing the low coverage whole genome sequencing (lcWGS) data of 716 individuals using Beagle, with the reference panel. The average imputation accuracy was 0.80, which was influenced by the minor allele frequency (MAF). GWAS was then performed to detect single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) and genes potentially associated with TL, using both the imputed and lcWGS datasets. The lcWGS and imputation-based GWAS identified 53 and 170 SNPs, annotating 58 and 111 candidate genes, respectively. Of which, 32 genes were shared between both approaches, including genes such as prex1 and ralgps2, which are related to TL. Additionally, several new genes, including mybph, atp5f1d, and ankrd24, were uniquely identified in the imputation-based GWAS. These results demonstrate a clear advantage combining genotype imputation with GWAS for lcWGS data. The approach provides an economically efficient method for expanding the available genotypic information in genomic evaluations, and also provided potential markers for selective breeding in T. ovatus.},
